segments.text: Of course, the corps commander, deputy commander, we did not interview his staff.
And company commanders were interviewed by the respective service, but I sat in on some of those.
But we only did the leadership jobs.
Can you give some examples of the kinds of questions, the kinds of concerns y'all had?

Well, we asked them the same sort of things you're asking, you know, what were their goals and what were they going to do about keeping the freshmen in the outfits and the attrition rate was one of the biggest problems we had and probably still have.
because there was such a change in lifestyle to go from high school into the Corps of Cadets.
And, you know, they need to understand that thoroughly and not try to run them, see how tough they are so they can run them off.
And I think that was the biggest thing we worked up, and so did the Corps, for the most part, the Corps style.
Do you remember any goofy answers that anybody gave?
Any that were humorous?
Oh, I really don't.
I think they were pretty well brief before they came in.
And about how long would these interviews last?
Probably an hour.
And that'd be in the spring?
Yes, before they...
I've forgotten when the... before the elephant walk came.
And General Simpson, incidentally, started interviewing, took over the interview process after he'd gotten his feet on the ground, but in my office.
Oh, did he come during your time?
Yes.
Oh, describe that.
Well, one day, Dr. Williams called me and
He says, this is on a Friday.
Tom, I got great news.
And I said, yes, sir.
And what's that?
And he said, we're going to get a Navy ROTC unit.
I said, Dr. Williams, that's not such great news.
He said, what do you mean?
I said, well, I'm trying to get Army officers and the Air Force, Air Force.
I don't want Navy Marines.
And he kind of laughed and he said, well, you got them.
And he says, I want you to come up here and I'm going to give you the application.
And you know how it is.
It was that fit.
And I need it by Monday morning.
And mind you, I don't have university staff.
I had an Army officer that we worked all weekend, an Air Force officer, putting that thing together.
And some of them had some skills on this job and were able to get the information out of the registrars and this, that, and the other.
But it was a real process.
Anyway, we met the deadline.
As far as you know, who were the key people in getting that approved in Washington?
General Simpson.
Simpson?
Yeah, sure.
He was the chief of personnel for the Marine Corps.
And I think Tiger Teague.
Tiger was involved, yes.
Congressman.
Yes, but General Simpson was the motivator.
Had you met him at the time of that application?
I had not.
When did you first meet him?
Well, it was probably shortly after that.
We had him down for a weekend football game.
I don't remember the exact date, but I was very impressed by him.
General Simpson was quite a person.
Describe him.
Make believe I'd never met him.
Describe him.
Well, you know, he was in the military all the way, and he was very well spoken when he speaks, when he was educated, and he spoke with authority.
If he didn't like what you're saying, you'd sit on his face, his lips would tremble, and many times they trembled in front of me because we didn't agree on everything.
The big change was he took me out of the chain of command with Dr. Williams, because I used to go directly with Dr. Williams.
So then I go directly to General Simpson.
It was very good having a direct chain, obviously.

And sometimes it did not work to my personal advantage because I was recommended by the Army to General Simpson that I, when I was preparing for retirement, be retired and do the job that these guys are doing now.
And General Simpson didn't even forward it.
And I couldn't go around and I wouldn't and so forth.
But I have that letter and I'm well aware of it.
And I was called by the Army and told about it and so forth because they wanted me in.
And I really wanted the job.
But they could have easily made me a Don Johnson, Texas militiaman and that sort of stuff.
But anyway, that was my only real conflict.
Where did he office?
I'm sorry?
General Simpson, where was his office located?
It was John Collis.
And let's bring Coldis in.
Coldis was not here when you arrived, was he?
They were still doing Hannigan and then Dr. Coldis.
Hannigan left.
As far as you know, why did he leave?
I have no idea.
I just thought he was ready to go.
And do you remember anything about the selection of John Coldis?
Do you remember his coming to campus?
I knew nothing about it.
I was very impressed with him from the very beginning.
Of course, a guy who's a workaholic and his memory for names, I just cannot believe it.
And, you know, at fish camp, like you used to do, I'm sure you're aware, you go around the room and everybody says, where are they from, and this, that, and the other.
I'll buy dinner for anybody that I can't recognize.
I never bought a dinner.
Let me, this is an editorial note to the typist.
As the new dean of faculties, I sat in on some of the interviews for the new vice president for student services, we called it then.
And we were all impressed with John Colas, but I was critical because I thought, my goodness, he's at East Texas State.
Surely we can attract somebody from some big, famous school.
And he wasn't an Aggie.
He wasn't a Texan.
He'd grown up in Gary, Indiana.
And I thought, my, my, my, how will he be able to understand this school and what we are?
Well, when he got here from the first day until the present,
All of us have been deeply, deeply impressed with him as a person, with his unfailing memory of people's names, with his constant smile, ceaseless work habits.
He was always, always trying to do what was best for Texas A&M and was a splendid, splendid choice for the job.
All right, now, end of note.
After he got here, what was your relationship as commandant to him as the vice president for students?
Well, I used to visit him regularly and talk about things.
And if there was something in the Corps, he'd talk to me about it and so forth.
So his door was open, no question about it, night or day.
And if there was a problem that related to the Corps, he'd call me at night and I'd take care of it the best I could.
and we just had a good working relationship.
I respected him a great deal.
Did they move, they didn't move to that house on the campus immediately, did they?
No, I don't know where the general deputy, I'm sorry, I'm in the admin building, the retired general that was on the head of the... Oh, Ludeke.
Ludeke, Ludeke was still living there.
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
did, what, as far as you could tell, what did cold us, what were his likes and his dislikes?
What pleased him most and what frustrated him most?

I'd say one, one thing that I never did much care about was, you know, with these weekly staff meetings we have, if it affected some personnel, people in the system, everybody had to vote on that sort of stuff, and I wasn't used to
voting on whether some guy's got a job or doesn't.

I'd talk to him myself, maybe, but I'd make the decision, and these decisions were made, I guess, on, well, I don't like this guy or I like this guy, you know, and when we first got an attorney over there, he was selected on that sort of basis, and so happened to be the one I liked the best, but that, to me, seemed like a command weakness, so to speak.
But I really never had any
run-ins with him of any major consequence and he supported me on everything that I did.
He tried to give me as much funding as he could.
This was a real difficult problem because I guess everybody had funding problems but for example we had a general almost every weekend and
Many of those came out of my pocket to take care of them.
I had no funds for renting a room or anything like that.
I couldn't ask one of them to pay their room rent, although most of them had orders and could have done it.
And most of them, as a matter of fact, did, but once in a while they didn't.
Things like that were kind of a problem.
And I'm glad to see the Commandant has more money than the President has, I think.
It's a troublesome thing for the military, and I went through this thing.
I had 36 general officers on campus for core things while I was commandant.
Wow.
It takes a lot of doings, and several of them stayed in our home, and I had four boys.
It wasn't easy.
They had to be friends also.
If these were friends, I wouldn't have invited them to my home.
Among all of those visitors, who were some of the most famous?
Great neighbors.
He was kind of my rabbi in the army.
And I admired him greatly.
I worked for him when I was a captain and a major.
And I'd send him on numerous occasions.
And the day he came down here was when Westport was having some problems up there.
They had this shooting incident.
And he got tears in his eyes for the Corps.
So that was great.
Well, you know, we had General Wyand, and he was the Air Force Chief of Staff.
And when he came down, he had some kind of accident and was in a calf, so he was kind of hard to handle.
But I've got a list of them.
I just hadn't gone over that one too much.
Most of them were Aggie oriented.
A great many of them were Aggies.
for any of those visitors, were there ever any incidents, any goofy things?
Never anything that came to my mind.

I will tell you, when an Air Force general was here, the Air Force was responsible for taking care of them, and they took care of one of these generals, I don't remember which one now, and he had a room over in the MSA, and they gave him the key, and they opened the door, and there was a man and his wife in bed, but they weren't doing anything, but they did.
Well, they didn't do a very good job of checking it out before that general got there.
Wrong room.
So he was somewhat upset about that, but I was pranking them.
I would have been, too.
In the first place, they should have gone with him and put him in the room.
In those days when you were commandant, did the Corps ever attempt any pranks involving a visitor?
No.
I've never heard of any.
No, they were always.
courteous and they respected those generals.
Most of those generals wanted to spend time over in the quad if they could, but the majority of them just flew in and flew out and they had busy schedules.
What did those visitors say to you about their impression of A&M and about the Corps?
Well, they were nothing but impressed.
As a matter of fact, the only reason I could come up with these names is I have letters from all of these people that wrote, and they were always good about
Thank you for what you and Mrs. Parsons did, and this, that, and the other.
And most of them were personalized, and they were very favorable.
Now, y'all were living where, you and your family?
We were down on Rosemary.
And how difficult was it, when you moved here, how difficult was it to find a house that you liked?
Well, I always had a large house when I was a colonel.
No, but I mean, was it difficult to find a house when you got here?
Oh, heck no.
Okay.
No, they hadn't money yet.
You know, Roadmap is a pretty good neighborhood.
And I built a house right there on the corner.
I've forgotten the address, across from the TV station.
And when my wife died, my son said he'd never spend another night there, so I packed the neighbor away.
But I loved it there.
And then I married again, and we lived in a rented place out there by that restaurant out on the road there, where they had a pond around it, I can't even remember the name of it, towards Kirkland.
Oh, going out east.
Right.
And then I built a home over on the other side.
Did the Corps ever attempt any pranks on your house?
No.
Or your car or anything like that?
If it was, we had, my wife had a Corvette, the other one, and it was egged one time, but I don't think it was Corps.
I think it was just people would do things.
It was probably against my kids.
Did the, were there ever any phone calls in the middle of the night?
Well, yeah.
From the war members you mean?
No, no, no jokes, no pranks.
No, I never had anything but good relations with them all the time.
The, I will tell one story, you know, I also was bonfire advisor, although I used Jerry Maynard mostly for that business,
But after I retired and was over at the police department and still under John Colders, I maintained that job.
And one night I got a call from a prof, and I can't remember his name, and I wouldn't want to name it anyway, but it lived over there and across the street from the bonfire.
And, you know, they turn that music up a few decibels, and this was 3, 3.15 in the morning.
And he identified himself, and, are you the bonfire advisor?
And he said,
Well, I want that damn music turned down.
I can't sleep, and it's so loud, and it's doing this, that, and the other, and I think it's totally irresponsible, and ranting and raving.
I said, yes, sir, I'll take care of it.
Well, I called him up, and I said, turn the damn music down.
It is wrong, and it shouldn't be blasting our way in it.
You've got to have that, get some earphones or something.
Well, they turned it down.
And I couldn't get back to sleep, and my wife couldn't.
So we just said, well, let's get up.
By now it's about 4.
I said, I'm going to call him back.
And I called him back, and I said, Dr. So-and-so, I just wanted to check and make sure everything was okay.
And wham, he slammed that thing down.
He hung up on me.
And so the next morning I went over to Dr. Kohler, and I said, John, I need to tell you this, because you'll probably get a phone call, but here's what I did.
And he laughed and said, that's good bull.
And he never got a phone call.
Describe the routine of Bonfire in your years.
Well, it was not near as sophisticated as it is nowadays.
We had the crane and all that stuff, but pretty much it was mostly core, although a good many of the civilian students worked on it.
It was not as closely supervised.
I went to the cutting areas and like that, but no more than just to walk around.
I never stayed out there.
And the, was it, when you got here, was it, had it been moved to the Duncan area?
It was the Duncan area.
Okay.
And were there, do you remember any accidents, any problems?
Well, no real problems other than, you know, once in a while somebody would get hurt.

We did have two students killed during this era, but it was bonfire related in that there were the freshman and sophomore who had worked all night, and when they got off the deal, they decided to take a trip over to the little house over there.
much sleep and he had a root bridge and killed him and I never of course told his parents what happened.
I just told them they were in an accident.
During the bonfire building in that era, it was only logs.
They were using chainsaws and heavy trucks and so forth.
Were they also organized as red pots and things like that?
They had this red pot hut, which I never went inside.
I knew what was going on in there.
What was it?
Some drinking?
Beer.
I told them they shouldn't have it out here, but I just did not enforce it.
I probably could have, but I didn't do it.
About how long did the cutting take?
Three weeks.
About three weeks.
And the bonfire in its shape was how many tiers high?
About four.
It wasn't a whole lot smaller than what they were doing over here.
And every year, you know, we set a limit and we'd go out there and check over the limit.
And it was always that way.
Did you or anybody else ever get any direction from someone outside about doing this or that?
Not really.
I never heard of anything.
Everybody was pretty positive.
The problem is that, you know, the students when they come to Bonfire are all loaded.
It was the former students out there raising hell, which I found out when I was in the police department because I used to have people in plain clothes around there and so was I.
And that was where the trouble spots were, with the nickel.
In terms of other Aggie traditions, from the Commandant's point of view, what role did the Commandant's office play for silver tap ceremonies?
Well, we cooperated with it.
I mean, turning the lights out and that sort of stuff.
And the officers were encouraged to attend, but most of them were Aggies anyway.
And we didn't have to do anything with nickel.
But you see, the light business was
still on them where everybody turned the lights off.
During my tenure here, it softened up on that, so it wasn't quite the same, but still the meaning is still the same.
Did you and your staff normally go to Silvertaps?
I went to them.
I, of course, don't know who went.
What about a home football weekend?
Describe the commandant's activities in the home football game.
Well, basically, he's taking care of whoever the guest is.
and making sure that they get to the president's mansion and to their game and all that sort of stuff.
Let's be the reviewing officer.
Right, because as far as the Corps, the Corps organized all that.
And, you know, we had people working with them and getting the tickets away from them.
Like I was telling my wife this morning, there will be a lot of Aggies in the Corps who ain't in the Corps.
because a lot of them couldn't get a ticket.
They'd put on a uniform and march in with them.
I bet you that happens too.
And normally did the reviewing officer come commercial air or did they come on a private?
Mostly it was military air, sometimes commercial, but they were pretty big wheels.
And then?
Would you take them to midnight yell practice?
If they wanted to go, but most of them didn't come to spend the night.
Oh, they came Saturday?
The big guys would just come in here and go to the review and go back.
Some of them spent the night, but those that wanted to go, we took them to midnight, but not many of them wanted to.
Do you remember some of the happy moments?
What were some of the nicest things you remember relating to those visitors and football games?
Well, it was, you know, all of them were just gentlemen.
Most of them had their wife or family sometimes, particularly if they were around from this area.
Oh, I'll tell you one.
It was General Patton when he was here.
This is the son of George S. Patton.
Right.
He did not like to be referred to as a son of General Patner, of course.
I don't blame him.
He's a gentleman in his own right, and he's a good one.
But he did something that surprised the hell out of me.
When we were on the reviewing stand, boy, he was impressed to beat hell.
And he says, you know, I know this ain't going to look good, but it's okay if I take pictures.
And he pulled a camera out, and he was just too shy taking pictures.
That impressed me.

because it's not exactly fully mirrored there, you know, but I could have told him, heck, we can get you all the pictures you want, but he, that stuck with me, and oh, I can't, my name, you'll know him, the black general we had over there who became the Prairie View president.
Oh, yes, yes.
I can't even remember right now, but he was two-star out of here, and
And he brought his family over and, you know, the Corps really liked him.
And he did walk around with them and that sort of stuff and do the things they liked.
And, of course, blacks were not many of them around in those days.
All right.
Back to your task during the football game.
So you would be hosting the visitor for the game.
Where did you all sit during the football games?
Usually up in the president's box there, you know, in the lower level.
after they got the sky box once in a while, he would invite us up there.
And then, when the game's over, then what?
Well, usually they were ready to go to bed or go home.
And if they were staying over, we'd take them out to dinner or have them in the house or something like that.
There was no entertainment to speak of.
Once in a while, there'd be some guy
One or two of them wanted to get in a poker game.
I don't gamble, but I knew some people that did.
We set that up, and that's a bunch of Aggies.
But they were no problem whatsoever, other than the fact that you're tied down.
You're not with the Corps.
You're with those people, as you should be.
During all of your years, did we ever have any international visitors?
I don't remember having any.
I don't remember any either.
I do remember another bonfire incident that you probably heard of and nobody may have brought it up.

One year after I was in the police department, I was standing over there by the huts they have out there where they're selling the cokes and things, and a car pulls up out there and stops, and a guy jumps out and runs into the bonfire and throws a Molotov on it, and there was a fireman from over at College Station.
And the kids around the bonfire, they took off running after him.
This guy, the car he was in, they took off and left him.
And he ran over across the street over in those houses over there.
And they were hot on his trail.
And he went into a home over there which happened to be occupied and rented to a bunch of girls and hid under a bed over there.
And they found him over there.
And fortunately, the police found him before the kids found him.
But... And he was a college station fireman?
Yes.
And he was, he was.
He was fired, of course, but.
And, and it, and the button.
It did not ignite it, but it could have.
You know, it hadn't been fueled or anything, but there's not no green logs.
It's not as easy as it looked, but it was just a Molotov cocktail.
But I had to be standing out there, and I got on, I had my radio, and I called the University Police, and told them they hot-footed, but College Station was already out there doing their job.
And during your years, as far as you were aware, did any of our students ever kidnap any of the other Southwest Conference mascots?
Well, yes, they did.
They got Bevo.
Can you share any information about that?
Well, I know he would not particularly want his name, but I'll tell you who it was, John Adams.
Well, you know John.
Oh, sure.
John was CO.
He's going to be there tonight.
Yeah, I know he will.
He's a very close friend of mine.
John was CO of Squadron 3.
And Squadron 3 engineered this thing.
And the first time I knew of it, I was in the office.
It was about 4, 35 o'clock in the morning.
This was shortly after my wife died.
And I couldn't, you know, get up and go right to the office.
I'm sitting there, and I hear all the noise.
And I headed for the quad.
And Dr. Williams headed for the quad.
at least I'm told.
And I saw that steer horns up and I turned and left and went back to the office.
Anyway, next morning, Dr. Williams and I got together and he was taking care of the business for the University of Texas.
And John was terribly afraid he was going to be kicked out of the university.
And his father was an Air Force colonel and he flew out from Florida

intercede and whatever i never had any attention i couldn't kick him out anyway i thought i recommended probably could have i thought you know it happened and uh i remember dr williams did a marvelous job of cooling that thing down but the true story when i asked john that's not long ago i'd always heard that on the way back they had a flat tire over in the caldwell
And they're fixing the flat and this highway patrol car pulls up.
And this guy asked him, you know, what are you boys up to?
We've got a flat.
We're trying to get this steer that we're taking over to vet college out to A&M.
And the guy walked around and looked at it and obviously knew what it was.
And he said, well, I'll tell you what I'm going to do.
And he had gloves on.
He took his gloves off and he put it up there.
And he says, I'm going to let you go this time.
He had an Aggie ring on him.
Oh, that's marvelous.
And I asked John, is that a true tale?
And John said, yes, it is.
Oh, that's marvelous.
That is marvelous.
And John may have asked me about it, but I'll tell you another one on John, too.
Well, he went in the Air Force for three months and then got out.
And he came by to see me and said he needed a job.
He said, you probably won't hire me because of it.
I said, John, what's that got to do with it?
Anyway, I did get a position for him one month, $9,000 a year.
This was 1973, I think.
Anyway, he worked for me two or three years there in the office and did an outstanding job.
We became very close.
still are, and I provided him a lot of input to his book because some idiot had told him that no U.S. Army unit ever reached the Yalu River during the war.
And I had told him about being on the Yalu River.
And he said, I'm not asking you on your word, but can you document it?
And I said, you bet I can document it.
I said, how would you like to see a picture of
Buffalo Bill Quinn, who was the regimental commander, and all the officers that could leave the place of duty pissing in the Yalu River.
And I have that.
Anyway, he said he didn't think he needed that, but I sent him a couple of articles.
But our regiment was the only regiment to reach it.
And we left it a lot faster than we got there, and we lost a lot of people.
unfortunately, but we got out before the other regiment at Reservoir.
We lost a lot of people at Reservoir.
I was good in Marines, but the Marines probably took the biggest loss.
But anyway, that's another Adam's tale there.
But my other Adam's tale that he doesn't want me to ever tell anybody, we were, I was
This time I was still a widower and we were talking about girls in the Corps and what they were going to wear and this, that, and the other.
And the uniformed people sent me six pair of pantyhose to ask me what color did they want us to stock.
I said, what the hell is it?
And I get John in.
And John knew about as much as me.
And I said, John?
You've got a problem here now.
You're working with this program.
And I said, here's a sample of the pantyhose.
I want to know what color do you recommend we use?
And I gave him the pantyhose, and that was his job.
And he said, don't you ever tell anybody that story.
In terms of all of the things to worry about and so forth,
Did, during your years, were there any attempts by anybody to try to kidnap Reveley?
I don't know of any, but I... And do you remember any...
